The ulnar nerve provides muscular branches to all intrinsic muscles of the hand, with the exception of the three thenar muscles and the lateral two lumbricals. It sends cutaneous branches to both sides of the medial portion of the hand (green).
remember, cubit is from cubitus (L) meaning elbow

Because the ulnar nerve does not pass through the carpal tunnel, the medial hand is spared in carpal tunnel syndrome. The most common site of ulnar entrapment is at the medial epicondyle, where the ulnar nerve is described as passing through the cubital tunnel     . The collection of signs and symptoms of entrapment here is called cubital tunnel syndrome. Numbness, pain and tingling in the medial hand is usually the first complaint. You have experienced this when you hit your funny bone, which is really a transient compression of the ulnar nerve when you bang your elbow against something.
